{{multiple issues| {{Original research|date=January 2012}} {{More citations needed|date=April 2011|talk=0}} }}
While some films criticize armed conflicts in a general sense, others focus on acts within a specific war, such as the use of poison gas or the [[Genocide|genocidal]] killing of civilians (e.g., ''[[Hotel Rwanda]]'', 2004). Some [[anti-war]] films such as ''[[Dr. Strangelove|Dr. Strangelove or: How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Bomb]]'' (1964) use [[parody]] and [[black comedy]] to [[satire|satirize]] wars and conflicts. An anti-war film's goal is to show the physical and psychological destruction warfare causes to the soldiers and to innocent civilians.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}
