{{tone|date=February 2017}} '''St James''' in [[Saint Peter Port]], [[Guernsey]], formerly called the church of '''St James-the-Less''', has since 1985 become a concert and assembly hall providing the island with a unique and versatile venue.
==History== In October 1815 Admiral [[James Saumarez, 1st Baron de Saumarez|James de Saumarez]] suggested the idea of building a church for use by the British garrison based in Guernsey where services could be held in English (as against French in other island churches). The church was designed by [[John Wilson (architect)|John Wilson]] and completed by 1818,<ref name="STJH">{{cite web |url=http://www.stjames.gg/history.php |title=History |publisher=stjames.gg}}</ref> <ref>{{cite book |last=Ring |first=Trudi [[et alii]] |title=Northern Europe: International Dictionary of Historic Places |publisher=Routledge |date=1996 |ISBN=978-1884964015}}</ref>{{rp|694}} at a cost of nearly £7,000.<ref>{{cite book |last=Toms |first=Carel |title=St Peter Port, People & Places |ISBN=1 86077 258 7 |date=2003}}</ref>{{rp|49}}
Sketched in 1832 by [[J. M. W. Turner]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tate.org.uk/art/artworks/turner-elizabeth-college-and-st-james-the-less-st-peter-port-french-stagecoach-caudebec-en-d23642 |title=Elizabeth College and St James-the-Less, St Peter Port; ?French Stagecoach; ?Caudebec-en-Caux ?1832 |publisher=Tate}}</ref> Used as a chapel by nearby [[Elizabeth College, Guernsey|Elizabeth College]].
In 1970 the church became redundant and started to decay until in 1981 ''The Friends of St James'' association was formed to restore and manage the building. The [[States of Guernsey]] agreed to pay for this restoration in 1983 and the building was officially re-opened on 5 July 1985 by HRH the [[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent|Duke of Kent]].<ref name=STJH/> The restoration of the building winning a [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/benet/region/Channel%20Islands |title=Schemes in Channel Islands |publisher=Civic Trust Awards}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caduquemin.com/Projects/Historical_Buildings/St__James.aspx |title=St. James |publisher=C.A. Duquemin |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref>
In 2002 the Dorey Centre, comprising meeting rooms, café and administration offices, were completed,<ref name=STJH/> which gave the centre additional facilities such as exhibition space and to cater for formal dinners and weddings. The gallery was chosen to house the Guernsey Millennium Tapestry.
==Features== * Whittaker Hall with superb acoustics for concerts,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visitguernsey.com/st-james-concert-hall |title=St James Concert Hall |publisher=Visit Guernsey |accessdate=12 April 2017}}</ref> can accommodate 576 people in theatre style seating or 217 for dinners * Dorey Room can seat 90 people * Founders Room can seat 35 * Walter Room, boardroom * Rothschild Room, boardroom * Café St James * Bailiwick of Guernsey Millennium Tapestry
==See also== * [http://www.stjames.gg/index.php St James website] * [http://www.guernseytapestry.org.gg/ Guernsey Tapestry] * Niven, Peter, ''St. James, Guernsey'', 2016, {{ISBN|978-1526200761}}
